= Appendix Presentation

== Objective

    - A presentation of your work is inherently aimed at individuals who have not yet read your text.
        Its primary goal is to engage and motivate them to explore your work further, showcasing its excellence and your pride in it.
    - Your presentation should effectively convey a key message: by the end, your audience should be able to articulate the main points of your talk in 2--3 sentences when discussing it with others.
        Your goal is for people to say, "I heard [your name] talk about [your topic], and it was really interesting because [highlight key takeaways]".



== Setting

- If you have a fixed time slot, always stay within your allotted time.
    Estimating the right amount of time for your presentation comes with practice.
- Consider your target audience's technical knowledge about your topic.
    Tailor your content accordingly to ensure everyone can follow along.
- Use the beginning of your talk as an "onboarding ramp".
    Briefly recap what your audience likely already knows, then smoothly transition into the new and exciting content of your presentation.
- Be mindful of your audience's engagement level, especially if your talk is part of a larger event.
    Capturing their attention may be challenging.


== Style

- Only include content on your slides that contributes to your main goal: ensuring your audience understands your work and finds it remarkable.
- Be mindful of transitions between slides.
    Keep in mind that every time you switch slides, you risk losing your audience's attention.
    Reveal new content together with your audience.
- Avoid including an agenda overview at the beginning unless your talk structure is unexpected.
    Use your speaking time and the audience's attention wisely.


== Visual Aspects

- Avoid using single-pixel-thick lines in diagrams, as they can be challenging for your audience to see.
- Be aware that the color contrast on a projector presentation might be worse than on your PC screen or laptop.
    Ensure that colors are distinct, and avoid using very dark or light colors.
- Use a readable font size, aiming for 7--10 lines of text per slide.
    If you need to include more text, make sure it provides clear benefits to your audience.
- Refrain from adding excessive text to a single slide.
    Either it's crucial and should be discussed during the presentation, or it's better left out.
    Reading lengthy passages can distract your audience from your spoken words.
- Don't include pictures on every slide just to fill space.
    Each visual element should serve a purpose and enhance your presentation.

